# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: signal-estimation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] In estimation theory and statistics, the **Cramér–Rao bound** (**CRB**) relates to estimation of a deterministic (fixed, though unknown) parameter.
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] The result is named in honor of Harald Cramér and Calyampudi Radhakrishna Rao, but has also been derived independently by Maurice Fréchet, Georges Darmois, and by Alexander Aitken and Harold Silverstone.
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] It is also known as Fréchet–Cramér–Rao or Fréchet–Darmois–Cramér–Rao lower bound.
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] It states that the precision of any unbiased estimator is at most the Fisher information; or (equivalently) the reciprocal of the Fisher information is a lower bound on its variance.
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] An unbiased estimator that achieves this bound is said to be (fully) *efficient*.
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] Such a solution achieves the lowest possible mean squared error among all unbiased methods, and is, therefore, the minimum variance unbiased (MVU) estimator.
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] However, in some cases, no unbiased technique exists which achieves the bound.
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] This may occur either if for any unbiased estimator, there exists another with a strictly smaller variance, or if an MVU estimator exists, but its variance is strictly greater than the inverse of the Fisher information.
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] The Cramér–Rao bound can also be used to bound the variance of *biased* estimators of given bias.
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] In some cases, a biased approach can result in both a variance and a mean squared error that are *below* the unbiased Cramér–Rao lower bound; see estimator bias.
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] Significant progress over the Cramér–Rao lower bound was proposed by Anil Kumar Bhattacharyya through a series of works, called Bhattacharyya bound.
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] The Cramér–Rao bound is stated in this section for several increasingly general cases, beginning with the case in which the parameter is a scalar and its estimator is unbiased.
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] All versions of the bound require certain regularity conditions, which hold for most well-behaved distributions.
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] These conditions are listed later in this section.
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] Suppose $\theta$ is an unknown deterministic parameter that is to be estimated from n independent observations (measurements) of x , each from a distribution according to some probability density function $f(x;\theta )$ .
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] and $\ell (x;\theta )=\log(f(x;\theta ))$ is the natural logarithm of the likelihood function for a single sample x and $\operatorname {E} _{x;\theta }$ denotes the expected value with respect to the density $f(x;\theta )$ of X .
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] If not indicated, in what follows, the expectation is taken with respect to X .
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] or the minimum possible variance for an unbiased estimator divided by its actual variance.
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] A more general form of the bound can be obtained by considering a biased estimator $T(X)$ , whose expectation is not $\theta$ but a function of this parameter, say, $\psi (\theta )$ .
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] Hence $E\{T(X)\}-\theta =\psi (\theta )-\theta$ is not generally equal to 0.
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] where $\psi '(\theta )$ is the derivative of $\psi (\theta )$ (by $\theta$ ), and $I(\theta )$ is the Fisher information defined above.
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] Apart from being a bound on estimators of functions of the parameter, this approach can be used to derive a bound on the variance of biased estimators with a given bias, as follows.
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] By the result above, any unbiased estimator whose expectation is $\psi (\theta )$ has variance greater than or equal to $(\psi '(\theta ))^{2}/I(\theta )$ .
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] The unbiased version of the bound is a special case of this result, with $b(\theta )=0$ .
[src:signal-estimation/cramér-rao-bound] It's trivial to have a small variance − an "estimator" that is constant has a variance of zero.
