[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] To calculate its expected value, it is convenient to rewrite the expression in terms of zero-mean random variables (statistical error) $\delta _{i}\equiv \mu -x_{i}$ .
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] This means that the estimator ${\widehat {\sigma }}^{2}$ is biased for $\sigma ^{2}$ .
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] It can also be shown that ${\widehat {\sigma }}$ is biased for $\sigma$ , but that both ${\widehat {\sigma }}^{2}$ and ${\widehat {\sigma }}$ are consistent.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In this case the MLEs could be obtained individually.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In general this may not be the case, and the MLEs would have to be obtained simultaneously.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] This maximum log-likelihood can be shown to be the same for more general least squares, even for non-linear least squares.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] This is often used in determining likelihood-based approximate confidence intervals and confidence regions, which are generally more accurate than those using the asymptotic normality discussed above.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] It may be the case that variables are correlated, or more generally, not independent.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Two random variables $y_{1}$ and $y_{2}$ are independent only if their joint probability density function is the product of the individual probability density functions, i.e.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Suppose one constructs an order-*n* Gaussian vector out of random variables $(y_{1},\ldots ,y_{n})$ , where each variable has means given by $(\mu _{1},\ldots ,\mu _{n})$ .
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Furthermore, let the covariance matrix be denoted by ${\mathit {\Sigma }}$ .
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In this and other cases where a joint density function exists, the likelihood function is defined as above, in the section "principles," using this density.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] $X_{1},\ X_{2},\ldots ,\ X_{m}$ are counts in cells / boxes 1 up to m; each box has a different probability (think of the boxes being bigger or smaller) and we fix the number of balls that fall to be n : $x_{1}+x_{2}+\cdots +x_{m}=n$ .
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Each box taken separately against all the other boxes is a binomial and this is an extension thereof.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Maximizing log likelihood, with and without constraints, can be an unsolvable problem in closed form, then we have to use iterative procedures.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] cannot be solved explicitly for an estimator ${\widehat {\theta }}={\widehat {\theta }}(\mathbf {y} )$ .
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Instead, they need to be solved iteratively: starting from an initial guess of $\theta$ (say ${\widehat {\theta }}_{1}$ ), one seeks to obtain a convergent sequence $\left\{{\widehat {\theta }}_{r}\right\}$ .
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] where the vector $\mathbf {d} _{r}\left({\widehat {\theta }}\right)$ indicates the descent direction of the *r*th "step," and the scalar $\eta _{r}$ captures the "step length," also known as the learning rate.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Gradient descent method requires to calculate the gradient at the *r*-th iteration, but no need to calculate the inverse of second-order derivative, i.e., the Hessian matrix.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Therefore, it is computationally faster than Newton–Raphson method.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] where $\mathbf {s} _{r}({\widehat {\theta }})$ is the score and $\mathbf {H} _{r}^{-1}\left({\widehat {\theta }}\right)$ is the inverse of the Hessian matrix of the log-likelihood function, both evaluated the *r*th iteration.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] But because the calculation of the Hessian matrix is computationally costly, numerous alternatives have been proposed.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Other quasi-Newton methods use more elaborate secant updates to give approximation of Hessian matrix.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] BFGS method is not guaranteed to converge unless the function has a quadratic Taylor expansion near an optimum.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Another popular method is to replace the Hessian with the Fisher information matrix, ${\mathcal {I}}(\theta )=\operatorname {\mathbb {E} } \left[\mathbf {H} _{r}\left({\widehat {\theta }}\right)\right]$ , giving us the Fisher scoring algorithm.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] This procedure is standard in the estimation of many methods, such as generalized linear models.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Although popular, quasi-Newton methods may converge to a stationary point that is not necessarily a local or global maximum, but rather a local minimum or a saddle point.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Therefore, it is important to assess the validity of the obtained solution to the likelihood equations, by verifying that the Hessian, evaluated at the solution, is both negative definite and well-conditioned.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Early users of maximum likelihood include Carl Friedrich Gauss, Pierre-Simon Laplace, Thorvald N.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] It was Ronald Fisher however, between 1912 and 1922, who single-handedly created the modern version of the method.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Maximum-likelihood estimation finally transcended heuristic justification in a proof published by Samuel S.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Wilks in 1938, now called Wilks' theorem.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The theorem shows that the error in the logarithm of likelihood values for estimates from multiple independent observations is asymptotically *χ* 2-distributed, which enables convenient determination of a confidence region around any estimate of the parameters.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The only difficult part of Wilks' proof depends on the expected value of the Fisher information matrix, which is provided by a theorem proven by Fisher.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Wilks continued to improve on the generality of the theorem throughout his life, with his most general proof published in 1962.
[src:signal-estimation/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Reviews of the development of maximum likelihood estimation have been provided by a number of authors.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Particle filtering uses a set of particles (also called samples) to represent the posterior distribution of a stochastic process given the noisy and/or partial observations.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The state-space model can be nonlinear and the initial state and noise distributions can take any form required.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Particle filter techniques provide a well-established methodology for generating samples from the required distribution without requiring assumptions about the state-space model or the state distributions.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] However, these methods do not perform well when applied to very high-dimensional systems.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Particle filters update their prediction in an approximate (statistical) manner.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The samples from the distribution are represented by a set of particles; each particle has a likelihood weight assigned to it that represents the probability of that particle being sampled from the probability density function.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Weight disparity leading to weight collapse is a common issue encountered in these filtering algorithms.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] However, it can be mitigated by including a resampling step before the weights become uneven.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Several adaptive resampling criteria can be used including the variance of the weights and the relative entropy concerning the uniform distribution.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] In the resampling step, the particles with negligible weights are replaced by new particles in the proximity of the particles with higher weights.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] From the statistical and probabilistic point of view, particle filters may be interpreted as mean-field particle interpretations of Feynman-Kac probability measures.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] These particle integration techniques were developed in molecular chemistry and computational physics by Theodore E.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Harris and Herman Kahn in 1951, Marshall N.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Rosenbluth in 1955, and more recently by Jack H.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] In computational physics, these Feynman-Kac type path particle integration methods are also used in Quantum Monte Carlo, and more specifically Diffusion Monte Carlo methods.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Feynman-Kac interacting particle methods are also strongly related to mutation-selection genetic algorithms currently used in evolutionary computation to solve complex optimization problems.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The particle filter methodology is used to solve Hidden Markov Model (HMM) and nonlinear filtering problems.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] From a statistical and probabilistic viewpoint, particle filters belong to the class of branching/genetic type algorithms, and mean-field type interacting particle methodologies.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The interpretation of these particle methods depends on the scientific discipline.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] In Evolutionary Computing, mean-field genetic type particle methodologies are often used as heuristic and natural search algorithms (a.k.a.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] In computational physics and molecular chemistry, they are used to solve Feynman-Kac path integration problems or to compute Boltzmann-Gibbs measures, top eigenvalues, and ground states of Schrödinger operators.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] In Biology and Genetics, they represent the evolution of a population of individuals or genes in some environment.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The origins of mean-field type evolutionary computational techniques can be traced back to 1950 and 1954 with Alan Turing's work on genetic type mutation-selection learning machines and the articles by Nils Aall Barricelli at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The first trace of particle filters in statistical methodology dates back to the mid-1950s; the 'Poor Man's Monte Carlo', that was proposed by John Hammersley et al., in 1954, contained hints of the genetic type particle filtering methods used today.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] In 1963, Nils Aall Barricelli simulated a genetic type algorithm to mimic the ability of individuals to play a simple game.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] In evolutionary computing literature, genetic-type mutation-selection algorithms became popular through the seminal work of John Holland in the early 1970s, particularly his book published in 1975.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] In Biology and Genetics, the Australian geneticist Alex Fraser also published in 1957 a series of papers on the genetic type simulation of artificial selection of organisms.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The computer simulation of the evolution by biologists became more common in the early 1960s, and the methods were described in books by Fraser and Burnell (1970) and Crosby (1973).
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Fraser's simulations included all of the essential elements of modern mutation-selection genetic particle algorithms.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] From the mathematical viewpoint, the conditional distribution of the random states of a signal given some partial and noisy observations is described by a Feynman-Kac probability on the random trajectories of the signal weighted by a sequence of likelihood potential functions.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Quantum Monte Carlo, and more specifically Diffusion Monte Carlo methods can also be interpreted as a mean-field genetic type particle approximation of Feynman-Kac path integrals.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The origins of Quantum Monte Carlo methods are often attributed to Enrico Fermi and Robert Richtmyer who developed in 1948 a mean-field particle interpretation of neutron chain reactions, but the first heuristic-like and genetic type particle algorithm (a.k.a.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Resampled or Reconfiguration Monte Carlo methods) for estimating ground state energies of quantum systems (in reduced matrix models) is due to Jack H.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] One can also quote the earlier seminal works of Theodore E.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Harris and Herman Kahn in particle physics, published in 1951, using mean-field but heuristic-like genetic methods for estimating particle transmission energies.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] In molecular chemistry, the use of genetic heuristic-like particle methodologies (a.k.a. pruning and enrichment strategies) can be traced back to 1955 with the seminal work of Marshall N.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The use of genetic particle algorithms in advanced signal processing and Bayesian inference is more recent.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] In January 1993, Genshiro Kitagawa developed a "Monte Carlo filter", a slightly modified version of this article appeared in 1996.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Gordon et al., published in their seminal work an application of genetic type algorithm in Bayesian statistical inference.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The authors named their algorithm 'the bootstrap filter', and demonstrated that compared to other filtering methods, their bootstrap algorithm does not require any assumption about that state space or the noise of the system.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Independently, the ones by Pierre Del Moral and Himilcon Carvalho, Pierre Del Moral, André Monin, and Gérard Salut on particle filters published in the mid-1990s.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Particle filters were also developed in signal processing in early 1989–1992 by P.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Salut in the LAAS-CNRS in a series of restricted and classified research reports with STCAN (Service Technique des Constructions et Armes Navales), the IT company DIGILOG, and the LAAS-CNRS (the Laboratory for Analysis and Architecture of Systems) on RADAR/SONAR and GPS signal processing problems.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The mathematical foundations and the first rigorous analysis of these particle algorithms are due to Pierre Del Moral in 1996.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The article also contains proof of the unbiased properties of a particle approximation of likelihood functions and unnormalized conditional probability measures.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The unbiased particle estimator of the likelihood functions presented in this article is used today in Bayesian statistical inference.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Dan Crisan, Jessica Gaines, and Terry Lyons, as well as Pierre Del Moral, and Terry Lyons, created branching-type particle techniques with various population sizes around the end of the 1990s.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Miclo made more advances in this subject in 2000.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Pierre Del Moral and Alice Guionnet proved the first central limit theorems in 1999, and Pierre Del Moral and Laurent Miclo proved them in 2000.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The first uniform convergence results concerning the time parameter for particle filters were developed at the end of the 1990s by Pierre Del Moral and Alice Guionnet.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The first rigorous analysis of genealogical tree-based particle filter smoothers is due to P.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The theory on Feynman-Kac particle methodologies and related particle filter algorithms was developed in 2000 and 2004 in the books.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] These abstract probabilistic models encapsulate genetic type algorithms, particle, and bootstrap filters, interacting Kalman filters (a.k.a.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Rao–Blackwellized particle filter), importance sampling and resampling style particle filter techniques, including genealogical tree-based and particle backward methodologies for solving filtering and smoothing problems.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] A particle filter's goal is to estimate the posterior density of state variables given observation variables.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The particle filter is intended for use with a hidden Markov Model, in which the system includes both hidden and observable variables.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The observable variables (observation process) are linked to the hidden variables (state-process) via a known functional form.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Similarly, the probabilistic description of the dynamical system defining the evolution of the state variables is known.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] A generic particle filter estimates the posterior distribution of the hidden states using the observation measurement process.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] the filtering problem is to estimate **sequentially** the values of the hidden states $X_{k}$ , given the values of the observation process $Y_{0},\cdots ,Y_{k},$ at any time step *k*.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The particle filter methodology provides an approximation of these conditional probabilities using the empirical measure associated with a genetic type particle algorithm.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] In contrast, the Markov Chain Monte Carlo or importance sampling approach would model the full posterior $p(x_{0},x_{1},...,x_{k}|y_{0},y_{1},...,y_{k})$ .
