[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Particle filters can be interpreted in many different ways.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] From the probabilistic point of view they coincide with a mean-field particle interpretation of the nonlinear filtering equation.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The updating-prediction transitions of the optimal filter evolution can also be interpreted as the classical genetic type selection-mutation transitions of individuals.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The sequential importance resampling technique provides another interpretation of the filtering transitions coupling importance sampling with the bootstrap resampling step.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] Last, but not least, particle filters can be seen as an acceptance-rejection methodology equipped with a recycling mechanism.
[src:signal-estimation/particle-filter-p01] The nonlinear filtering evolution can be interpreted as a dynamical system in the set of probability measures of the form $\eta _{n+1}=\Phi _{n+1}\left(\eta _{n}\right)$ where $\Phi _{n+1}$ stands for some mapping from the set of probability distribution into itself.
